alternatives.transcript: Hi there. This is a video on the c d or change directory command in Linux. Basically, it is your way of navigating through the file system. So c d stands for change directory. Okay. To change to your home directory, I happen to be in my home directory. Let's say I wasn't, let's say you're in one zero seven assignments, assignment zero, whatever. If I wanna change to my home directory, I can either type c d tilde, which does that. C d minus, by the way, goes back to the previous directory. Or I can just type c d and c d also takes you to your home directory. To change to the parent directory, so if I go back to the sign zero directory and I wanna go to the parent directory, I can do that by just typing cd dot dot and that will take me up to the assignments directory and cd dot dot again will take me to the cs one hundred seven directory etc. By the way, if I'm in assignments assign zero I can type c d dot dot slash dot dot slash dot dot and that will take me all the way back to my home directory because it just kinda climbs up the directories. Remember dot dot just means the previous directory. So if you go the previous directory slash the previous directory slash the previous directory, it will go all the way back to your main commands. So that's really about it for the cd command. There's not too much more to it except to say that you should get very used to using it and very used to using it with the dot dot and with the tilde. So for instance if I wanted to change to, let's say I was in CS107 assignments and I wanted to change to CS107 old, I could type cd cs107old and that would take me right there. Right? So that's how it works. Thanks.
